        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We are only interested in dust continuum emission, so we chose the "Single Continuum" setup in the spectral type mode. </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The angular resolution of  0.5'' was chosen as a trade-off between angular resolution and surface brightness sensitivity. Observations with poorer angular resolutions would not have enough resolution to distinguish the two models described above; improving the resolution by a factor of  2 would give a lower surface brightness sensitivity by a factor of 4 and the dust emission would not be detectable, in a reasonable amount of time, at good enough signal-to-noise ratio to distinguish the two models.

According to the Technical Handbook an angular resolution of 0.5'' is obtained in Band 6 with the
array configuration C36-3.

In terms of spatial filtering, the largest angular scale which is recoverable with the C36-3 array configuration, i.e. 10.9'' in Band 6, is very close to the diameter of the disk, which is of  11''. From our simulations, we expect to recover about 75% of the total disk emission. In order to recover the emission on the largest scales we will combine the Cycle 3 data with the previous Cycle 0 ones which did not suffer of any spatial filtering because of the shorter baselines. For this reason we do not need any observations in a compact configuration in Cycle 3.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Sensitivity in continuum was chosen so that our observations can well distinguish between models with a gap and double power-law distribution. This is demonstrated by the ALMA simulations discussed in the text of the proposals. We do not request observations in any line.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We chose a sky frequency of 239.5 GHz because this would give us a better signal-to-noise ratio (considering the mm-SED of the disk) than would be obtained using the standard frequency. Note also that this is the same frequency of our previous Cycle 0 observations, so that it will be possible to combine our new dataset with the previous one.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_NON_STD_CONT_FREQ</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
    </prj:ScienceGoal>
