    <prp:abstract>We propose to observe the dust thermal emission of the debris disk around the young Solar analog HD 107146. Our Cycle 0 observations for this system showed a very intriguing decrease of surface brightness inside the disk. However, because of the limited sensitivity and angular resolution of the Cycle 0 data we could not distinguish between models with a fully depleted gap and double power-law models where the decrease in density is more smooth.
Thanks to the better sensitivity and angular resolution available in Cycle 3 we will be able to distinguish between these two scenarios. If the gap is real, this will provide evidence for the presence of a Super Earth planet orbiting a Solar-like star at an orbital radius of about 80 AU. This would confirm models of planet formation via planetesimal accretion which predict the formation of planets with these characteristics at the age and mass of HD 107146. In the case of a double power-law distribution for the dust density, this system would represent a test bed for models of planetesimal belts in which the formation of Pluto-sized bodies trigger an efficient production of dust. </prp:abstract>
